1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,640
Stan has one big thing due tomorrow.

2
00:00:02,640 --> 00:00:06,000
So tonight he sits down to finally start it.

3
00:00:06,000 --> 00:00:09,680
And then somehow the kitchen really needs cleaning.

4
00:00:09,680 --> 00:00:12,160
His desk needs reorganizing.

5
00:00:12,160 --> 00:00:14,760
He should probably reply to that email first.

6
00:00:14,760 --> 00:00:18,080
He watches one video, just one.

7
00:00:18,080 --> 00:00:22,000
The whole night, Stan is busy, Stan is moving,

8
00:00:22,000 --> 00:00:25,640
and Stan does not touch the one thing he actually has to do.

9
00:00:25,640 --> 00:00:28,280
And he feels terrible the entire time.

10
00:00:28,280 --> 00:00:30,560
Now, here's the giveaway.

11
00:00:30,560 --> 00:00:33,080
Stan is not being lazy.

12
00:00:33,080 --> 00:00:36,240
Lazy is when you do not even want to do the thing.

13
00:00:36,240 --> 00:00:40,240
Stan desperately wants to, and he still cannot make himself start.

14
00:00:40,240 --> 00:00:42,400
That is something else entirely.

15
00:00:42,400 --> 00:00:44,480
So what is actually going on?

16
00:00:44,480 --> 00:00:47,160
Because procrastination is not laziness.

17
00:00:47,160 --> 00:00:48,960
It is not bad planning.

18
00:00:48,960 --> 00:00:51,360
And the ancient Greeks were so obsessed with it

19
00:00:51,360 --> 00:00:53,280
that they gave it its own name.

20
00:00:53,280 --> 00:00:56,440
We are taught that procrastination is basically laziness

21
00:00:56,440 --> 00:00:58,880
or being bad with time.

22
00:00:58,880 --> 00:01:02,200
So the fix we are handed is always the same.

23
00:01:02,200 --> 00:01:05,560
Try harder, get a planner, have more discipline,

24
00:01:05,560 --> 00:01:07,480
and that advice almost never works.

25
00:01:07,480 --> 00:01:08,920
There is a reason for that.

26
00:01:08,920 --> 00:01:11,680
It is aimed at the wrong problem entirely.

27
00:01:11,680 --> 00:01:15,400
Because procrastination has almost nothing to do with time.

28
00:01:15,400 --> 00:01:17,040
It has to do with feeling.

29
00:01:17,040 --> 00:01:18,600
When you sit down to face a task,

30
00:01:18,600 --> 00:01:21,080
your brain does not just see the task.

31
00:01:21,080 --> 00:01:22,920
It feels something about it.

32
00:01:22,920 --> 00:01:25,760
Maybe boredom, maybe anxiety,

33
00:01:25,800 --> 00:01:28,200
maybe a quiet fear that you will try

34
00:01:28,200 --> 00:01:30,320
and it still will not be good enough.

35
00:01:30,320 --> 00:01:33,040
And your brain, more than almost anything,

36
00:01:33,040 --> 00:01:35,520
wants that bad feeling to stop right now.

37
00:01:35,520 --> 00:01:38,600
So it reaches for the one move that kills it instantly.

38
00:01:38,600 --> 00:01:40,360
It avoids the task.

39
00:01:40,360 --> 00:01:42,480
That is all procrastination is.

40
00:01:42,480 --> 00:01:44,120
Not laziness.

41
00:01:44,120 --> 00:01:47,240
Mood repair, a quick hit of relief in the present,

42
00:01:47,240 --> 00:01:50,480
put on a credit card that your future self has to pay.

43
00:01:50,480 --> 00:01:52,680
And this is exactly why procrastination

44
00:01:52,680 --> 00:01:55,800
is basically the opposite of laziness.

45
00:01:55,800 --> 00:01:57,480
We covered laziness already.

46
00:01:57,480 --> 00:02:01,480
And a lot of what we call being lazy is actually this.

47
00:02:01,480 --> 00:02:04,960
Real laziness is simply not wanting to do the thing.

48
00:02:04,960 --> 00:02:07,080
Procrastination is the reverse.

49
00:02:07,080 --> 00:02:09,440
You want to do it, you fully intend to,

50
00:02:09,440 --> 00:02:11,560
you swear you will start in five minutes

51
00:02:11,560 --> 00:02:13,280
and you avoid it anyway.

52
00:02:13,280 --> 00:02:15,120
That gap between wanting to do it

53
00:02:15,120 --> 00:02:18,920
and still not doing it is exactly why it eats at you.

54
00:02:18,920 --> 00:02:21,400
And there is a cruel little twist baked in.

55
00:02:21,400 --> 00:02:23,920
The one who pays the bill is future you.

56
00:02:23,920 --> 00:02:27,120
And your brain treats future you almost like a stranger.

57
00:02:27,120 --> 00:02:29,280
Present you grabs the relief.

58
00:02:29,280 --> 00:02:32,720
Future you is the one panicking at two in the morning.

59
00:02:32,720 --> 00:02:34,720
And here is the strangest part.

60
00:02:34,720 --> 00:02:36,560
The people who procrastinate the most

61
00:02:36,560 --> 00:02:38,960
are often the ones who care the most.

62
00:02:38,960 --> 00:02:41,560
Because if you are terrified of doing it badly,

63
00:02:41,560 --> 00:02:43,320
the bad feeling is even bigger.

64
00:02:43,320 --> 00:02:46,040
So you flinch away even harder.

65
00:02:46,040 --> 00:02:48,480
Now, if you think this is a modern problem,

66
00:02:48,480 --> 00:02:50,560
something phones and streaming did to us,

67
00:02:50,600 --> 00:02:52,520
the ancient Greeks would laugh.

68
00:02:52,520 --> 00:02:55,160
They were fascinated by this exact puzzle.

69
00:02:55,160 --> 00:02:58,560
Thousands of years ago, they even had a word for it,

70
00:02:58,560 --> 00:03:00,040
Akrasia.

71
00:03:00,040 --> 00:03:03,400
It means doing something even while you know fully

72
00:03:03,400 --> 00:03:05,280
that it goes against your better judgment.

73
00:03:06,560 --> 00:03:08,800
Socrates and Aristotle genuinely argued

74
00:03:08,800 --> 00:03:11,040
about how it is even possible.

75
00:03:11,040 --> 00:03:13,720
How can a person know the smart thing to do?

76
00:03:13,720 --> 00:03:16,800
Truly know it and still not do it.

77
00:03:16,800 --> 00:03:19,400
Procrastination is not a bug of the modern world.

78
00:03:19,400 --> 00:03:22,240
It is one of the oldest riddles of being human.

79
00:03:22,240 --> 00:03:26,720
And the word we use is a tiny confession all on its own.

80
00:03:26,720 --> 00:03:29,760
Procrastinate comes from Latin, pro,

81
00:03:29,760 --> 00:03:33,840
meaning forward and cras, meaning tomorrow.

82
00:03:33,840 --> 00:03:36,080
Put them together and it literally means

83
00:03:36,080 --> 00:03:38,200
to put it forward to tomorrow.

84
00:03:38,200 --> 00:03:40,800
Humans have been doing this so reliably

85
00:03:40,800 --> 00:03:43,240
for so long that we built a word for it

86
00:03:43,240 --> 00:03:45,520
out of the actual word for tomorrow.

87
00:03:45,520 --> 00:03:48,000
So here's the part that turns everything

88
00:03:48,080 --> 00:03:50,040
you have been told upside down.

89
00:03:50,040 --> 00:03:53,280
Because procrastination runs on bad feelings,

90
00:03:53,280 --> 00:03:56,320
the way most of us fight it actually feeds it.

91
00:03:56,320 --> 00:03:59,440
You put the thing off, then you call yourself lazy

92
00:03:59,440 --> 00:04:02,360
and useless and ask what is wrong with you.

93
00:04:02,360 --> 00:04:03,880
And now there is a whole new layer

94
00:04:03,880 --> 00:04:05,960
of bad feelings stuck to that task.

95
00:04:05,960 --> 00:04:07,960
So the next time you go to start it,

96
00:04:07,960 --> 00:04:10,360
there is even more to flinch away from.

97
00:04:11,680 --> 00:04:13,480
Guilt is not the cure.

98
00:04:13,480 --> 00:04:15,280
Guilt is the fuel.

99
00:04:15,280 --> 00:04:17,120
The harder you beat yourself up,

100
00:04:17,120 --> 00:04:20,080
the bigger and scarier the thing becomes.

101
00:04:20,080 --> 00:04:22,480
Which leads to the most backward sounding fix

102
00:04:22,480 --> 00:04:23,680
in all of psychology.

103
00:04:23,680 --> 00:04:26,000
And it is a real study.

104
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:28,960
Researchers track students across their exams.

105
00:04:28,960 --> 00:04:31,160
The students who simply forgave themselves

106
00:04:31,160 --> 00:04:33,960
for procrastinating before the first exam

107
00:04:33,960 --> 00:04:37,520
went on to procrastinate less before the next one.

108
00:04:37,520 --> 00:04:39,680
Not the most disciplined students,

109
00:04:39,680 --> 00:04:41,040
the most forgiving ones.

110
00:04:41,040 --> 00:04:44,920
Because once you drop the guilt, the task stops radiating

111
00:04:45,880 --> 00:04:49,480
and it quietly turns back into just a task.

112
00:04:49,480 --> 00:04:52,360
The secret was never to be harder on yourself.

113
00:04:52,360 --> 00:04:54,760
It was to stop making the thing feel so awful

114
00:04:54,760 --> 00:04:57,520
to walk up to and then to shrink it.

115
00:04:57,520 --> 00:05:01,080
Not write the essay, write one bad sentence,

116
00:05:01,080 --> 00:05:04,000
make the first step too small to be scary.

117
00:05:04,000 --> 00:05:05,720
So the next time you are Stan,

118
00:05:05,720 --> 00:05:07,400
scrubbing a perfectly clean kitchen

119
00:05:07,400 --> 00:05:09,840
to avoid the thing you swore you would do,

120
00:05:09,840 --> 00:05:11,400
do not reach for the guilt.

121
00:05:11,400 --> 00:05:14,360
That is the trap that keeps the whole loop spinning.

122
00:05:14,360 --> 00:05:17,640
You are not lazy and you are not broken.

123
00:05:17,640 --> 00:05:19,480
You are doing one of the most human things

124
00:05:19,480 --> 00:05:22,280
there is quietly trading a little peace now

125
00:05:22,280 --> 00:05:24,160
for a little panic later.

126
00:05:24,160 --> 00:05:27,840
The Greeks never did solve it, but they understood it.

127
00:05:27,840 --> 00:05:29,880
And it turns out that understanding it

128
00:05:29,880 --> 00:05:32,040
and going a little easier on yourself

129
00:05:32,040 --> 00:05:34,920
is the closest thing we have ever found to a cure.
